    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>Using the utility I describe <a href=\"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/10900869/how-do-i-write-a-method-which-would-work-on-both-lists-and-arrays/10901267#10901267\">here</a>, you can have a more control over the string representation you get for your array.</p>\n\n<pre><code>String[] s = { \"hello\", \"world\" };\nRichIterable&lt;String&gt; r = RichIterable.from(s);\nr.mkString();                 // gives \"hello, world\"\nr.mkString(\" | \");            // gives \"hello | world\"\nr.mkString(\"&lt; \", \", \", \" &gt;\"); // gives \"&lt; hello, world &gt;\"\n</code></pre>\n"
